etadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0a571107dd3e09540490629e7cc5fd0f886d2653d3de89eec689a84f0e9502ca"}, "3": {"node_id": "81b331da-1743-4b8e-8546-1e698a3001ca", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3556cc183df4c3cac3c7342d14a5aa3987c418540fb82db9616f00a1e5bb4476"}}, "hash": "8418ab7d0a1a3c74496b3f3b26a31131b9ec8393386eed7c13db6a5593882705", "text": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action 9th International Congress on AIDS in Asia and the Pacifc Symposium Report Tuesday, 11 August 2009 ICRW Copyright \u00a9 2010 Photos by Shaju John ISBN 978-974-680-267-3 Regional HIV & Development Programme for Asia & the Pacifc UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok United Nations Service Building, 3rd Floor Rajdamnern Nok Ave. Bangkok, Thailand Email: regionalcentrebangkok@undp.org Tel: +66 (2) 288-2129 Fax: +66 (2) 288-3032 Web: http://regionalcentrebangkok.undp.or.th/ Acknowledgments This report summarizes the presentations, discussions and recommendations made at the Symposium \u201cHIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action\u201d held on 11 August 2009 at the 9th International Congress on AIDS in Asia and the Pacifc (ICAAP IX) in Bali, Indonesia as part of a series of symposia supported by the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP). The intention of this publication is to stimulate debate and action on HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission in the region beyond the life of the Conference. The organization of the symposium would not have been possible without the close collaboration of our partners: the Joint United Nations Programme on AIDS (UNAIDS), Women of Asia Pacifc Network of people living with HIV (WAPN+), the United Nations Devel- opment Fund for Women (UNIFEM), the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA), the International Centre for Research on Women (ICRW) and the support of the ICAAP IX secretariat and the Government of Indonesia. Our thanks and gratitude to Dr. Nafs Sadik, UN Secretary General\u2019s Special Envoy for HIV/AIDS in Asia Pacifc and J.V.R. Prasada Rao, Director, UNAIDS Regional Support Team for Asia and the Pacifc for chairing the symposium. We would like to gratefully acknowledge the contribution of the panelists and discussants: Dr. Nafsiah Mboi, Secretary, National AIDS Commission, Indonesia; Caitlin Wiesen, Regional HIV Practice Leader, UNDP Regional Centre for Asia and the Pacifc; Caroline Thomas, WAPN+; Geeta Rao Gupta, President, ICRW; Rafy Martinez, Migrant Health Advocate, ACHIEVE Inc. and Anandi Yuvaraj, Coordinator of the International Community of Women Living with HIV and AIDS for their invaluable insight that made this event a success. The symposium and follow-up report was organized by the UNDP Regional HIV Practice team for Asia Pacifc under the leadership of Caitlin Wiesen. Special thanks to Ferdinand Strobel assisted by Durga Pulendran and Ramaaya Salgado for coordinating the sympo- sium and the production of this report; to Asha Krishnakumar for the initial draft and to Ian Mungall for the design and layout. 1 Introduction The HIV epidemics across Asian countries are diverse and complex. Yet despite the differences that ex- ist, the national epidemics share common characteristics such as being centered mainly around unpro- tected paid sex, the sharing of contaminated injection drug equipment and unprotected sex between men. An estimated 75 million men in Asia visit sex workers and 10 million women cater to them. Add to these figures male Intravenous Drug Users (IDUs) and Men who have Sex with Men (MSM) - approximately 20 million - and we have a very large number of people who are at high risk of getting infected and, in turn, can potentially infect their partners. Since most men who buy sex are either married or will get married, significant numbers of ostensibly \u2018low risk\u2019 women who only have sex with their husbands are exposed to HIV. A conservative estimate by the Commission on AIDS in Asia put this number at 50 million women1. In 2008, women accounted for 35 per cent of all adult HIV infections in Asia \u2013 up from 17 per cent in 1990. Evidence from several Asian countries shows that these women are either married or in long-term relationships with men who engage in high-risk sexual behaviors. Studies in Asia show that almost all new infections among women are contracted through marriage2. In India alone, approximately 90 per cent of the 1.7 million women living with HIV were infected by their husbands or partners while in long- term relationships3.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "81b331da-1743-4b8e-8546-1e698a3001ca": {"__data__": {"id_": "81b331da-1743-4b8e-8546-1e698a3001ca", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0a571107dd3e09540490629e7cc5fd0f886d2653d3de89eec689a84f0e9502ca"}, "2": {"node_id": "a9806251-2336-4f78-93b7-0a4bc7a0704a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8418ab7d0a1a3c74496b3f3b26a31131b9ec8393386eed7c13db6a5593882705"}}, "hash": "3556cc183df4c3cac3c7342d14a5aa3987c418540fb82db9616f00a1e5bb4476", "text": "A report by a joint UN initiative (UNAIDS, UNDP, UNIFEM, UNFPA) with regional partners such as the ASEAN Foundation and networks of people living with HIV confirms this trend and points to rampant intimate partner violence across social and economic strata as an additional aspect in the increase of Intimate Partner Transmission of HIV4. Intimate partner violence (physical and/or sexual) is a particular cause for concern as a very significant factor that compounds both directly and indirectly Intimate Partner Transmission of HIV. In India, Ban- gladesh and Nepal women who were exposed to intimate partner violence from husbands infected with HIV through unprotected sex with multiple partners were seven times more likely to acquire HIV compared to", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1c8b4e68-33bd-49a3-8ce1-88f51a1c110a": {"__data__": {"id_": "1c8b4e68-33bd-49a3-8ce1-88f51a1c110a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "70c4e18b84a47fd5dd25d030b7a12385d17dc878ce8cbf256f857b0a9eecede5"}, "3": {"node_id": "cbb77860-a746-49f7-9de4-a85c96b00b92", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2d7c627f87755c58ecc7952c998847c808db8fec553fffd5eb707bf035d93cc9"}}, "hash": "4cde6e9b01eb1c73f642df93e3320df892243c8b9bdedeec1ce273bf0f1d0a30", "text": "women not exposed to violence and whose husbands did not have sex with multiple partners5. Evidence from some countries shows that men are more likely to hide, or delay, the disclosure of their HIV status to their partners, compared to women6. This prevents regular condom use and hence higher transmission of HIV. Furthermore, women\u2019s subjugation and low status in society and within the house- hold gives them very little power to negotiate safe sex. This makes it particularly difficult for women generally, and \u2018married\u2019 women specifically to protect themselves from HIV exposure and ultimately infection through sex with their lifelong partner. The culture of silence that surrounds sex7, gender inequality, violence and discrimination that are so pervasive in the region exacerbate the problem8. Migration and mobility facilitate the spread of HIV. Most migrants are separated from spouses and fami- lies, and are often pushed into poor working and living conditions without recreational activities lead- ing to isolation and stress. Across Asia, in male dominated migrant workforces such as the ones found on construction sites, commercial fisheries, extracting industries and plantations, men find themselves in worksite subcultures in which the purchase of sexual services is common. As a result, they have a high risk of acquiring HIV, and passing it on to their partners when they return home infected9. 1 Commission on AIDS in Asia, 2008 2 Commission on AIDS in Asia, 2008 3 Silverman J.G. et al., Intimate partner violence and HIV infection among married Indian women, JAMA, 2008 4 HIV Transmission in Intimate Partner Relationships in Asia, UNAIDS, August 2009 5 Dr. Prasada Rao, Director, UNAIDS Regional Support Team for Asia and the Pacific, quoting Decker et al., Intimate partner violence is both a risk marker and a transmission mechanism for women\u2019s HIV infection: Findings from a national population-based sample of Indian husband-wife dyads, JAIDS, 2009 6 Caitlin Wiesen, HIV Practice Team Leader, UNDP Regional Centre for Asia and the Pacific (from China HIV/AIDS Survey Data, UNDP, 2009) 7 Geeta Rao Gupta, President, ICRW 8 Dr. Nafis Sadik, UN Secretary General\u2019s special envoy on HIV/AIDS in Asia and the Pacific 9 HIV Transmission in Intimate Partner Relationships in Asia, UNAIDS, August 2009 INTRoDUCTIoN 2 Traditional expectations related to masculinity and male sexual behaviour also increase the risk of in- fection among men and boys. Typical male roles that call for men and boys to be tough, aggressive, sexually dominant, and risk-taking are often associated with behaviours that increase men\u2019s HIV risk. In particular, having multiple sexual partners, use of drugs or alcohol, and poor health seeking behavior increase the risk of acquiring sexually transmitted infections10. The mutually harmful nature of some gender norms underscores the importance of involving men and boys in any effort towards change. An important yet rarely acknowledged factor that potentially influences men\u2019s extramarital sexuality is the social construction of marriage, that is, the emotional, cultural, and economic meanings of conju- gality in a society. \u201cUnderstanding and addressing HIV transmission among intimate part- ners is therefore one of the most complex, difficult and sensitive areas but it is also the key to dealing with the rapidly rising HIV epidemic in the region and may even be the key to turning it around\u201d 11 If sustained and effective programmes to curb HIV transmission in commercial sex, drug injection, and male-to-male sex are established, countries are likely to see a steady decrease in spousal transmission12. Realising the complexity and importance of this issue for tackling Asian epidemics, the 9th Interna- tional Congress on AIDS in Asia and the Pacific (ICAAP), convened on 11 August 2009 the symposium: \u201cHIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action\u201d. Jointly organized by UNDP, WAPN+, UNAIDS, UNIFEM, UNFPA and ICRW the symposium took stock of emerging evidence, facilitated the exchange of ideas and perspectives and proposed critical policy and programme responses to begin to halt and reverse Intimate Partner Transmission of HIV in Asia. This report summarises the presentations, statements and recommendations from leaders, academi- cians, policy-makers, activists and people living with HIV made during the event.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "cbb77860-a746-49f7-9de4-a85c96b00b92": {"__data__": {"id_": "cbb77860-a746-49f7-9de4-a85c96b00b92", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-a