9-467b-8fde-c640838380d1": {"__data__": {"id_": "11282b6a-3239-467b-8fde-c640838380d1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "47cacf22b355c0c983e5ae8c402439e0f08ae300b7d7dfdec8f4e9acd52b8271"}, "3": {"node_id": "a2389bf7-d2f2-4767-930e-1baf79d3f2c0", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3c7d786c8c0f757f152f6acafd5c313ef701d87d34a600f7629bec701064fbf1"}}, "hash": "d05f43fb0ed1782583aa1c6d2b21944008279023c0581c544c8ab7f4290a7384", "text": "11, 2009, 14:00 to 15:30 Hours Place: Nusa Indah, Bali International Convention Centre, Westin Hotel, Bali organizers: UNDP, WAPN+, UNAIDS, UNIFEM, UNFPA and ICRW Chairpersons: Dr. Nafis Sadik, UN Secretary General\u2019s Special Envoy for HIV/AIDS in Asia and the Pacific Introductory Remarks J.V.R. Prasada Rao, Director, UNAIDS Regional Support Team for Asia and the Pacific Rationale for Discussion on Intimate Partner Transmission Panelists: Dr. Nafsiah Mboi, Secretary, National AIDS Commission, Indonesia The Challenges of Engendering National AIDS Programmes Including Low Risk Women Caitlin Wiesen, Regional HIV Practice Leader, UNDP Regional Centre for Asia and the Pacific Introduction to Intimate Partner Transmission in the Asian Region Caroline Thomas, WAPN+, Indonesia How Do Positive Women See Intimate Partner Transmission? Geeta Rao Gupta, President, ICRW The Gender Dimensions of HIV Transmission in Intimate Partner Relationships Raffy Martinez, Migrant Health Advocate, ACHIEVE Inc. Mobility, Families and HIV Vulnerability Discussant: Anandi Yuvaraj, Coordinator, International Community of Women Living with HIV/AIDS Key Challenges Key Recommendations 3 5 Introductory Remarks The compelling evidence presented in the Commission on AIDS in Asia 2008 report has changed the way we think about HIV in Asia. It should also change the direction of policy to prevent and control the spread of HIV and AIDS. As the report notes, not only has the proportion of women among people living with HIV been rising steadily, but many of these women are married women who are overwhelmingly monogamous. The vast majority of them have acquired their infection from their partners, who are buyers of unprotected sex. Research also shows that spousal violence - domestic and sexual - is widespread, and not confi ned to the lower socio-economic groups as once thought. \u201cProgrammes addressing the particularly critical intersection of violence and HIV risk and reducing high-risk behavior on the part of men are few. In general, policies and interventions to better address the social determinants of HIV risk in the region are urgently needed.\u201d Reacting to a proposition that married women in Asia should be regarded as a \u201chigh risk group\u201d, respon- dents from across the region participating to an E-Discussion on Intimate Partner Transmission hosted by UNDP raised the following points: \u2022\ufffd The focus needs to be on understanding and addressing the high\u2013risk sexual behaviors of married men. There needs to be a better understanding of why men go to sex workers and the complex and multidimensional determinants of extramarital sex as well as the political economy of marriage in the various Asian contexts. It was noted that one of the eff ects of insisting on condom use by men who are clients of sex workers has reduced the proportion of men seeking commercial sex, which is a signifi cant fi nding in itself. Underlying issues of gender-based violence, and spousal violence in particular and overall gender inequality are central to married women\u2019s HIV vulnerability in Asia. \u2022\ufffd The heightened HIV risk vulnerability of migrant workers - male and female \u2013 and in turn their partners\u2019, is a neglected area. Migrants away from home for extended periods of time have a well Dr. Nafi s Sadik, a national of Pakistan, is Special Adviser to the UN Secretary-General and his Special Envoy for HIV/AIDS in Asia and the Pacifi c, with the rank of Under-Secretary-General. In 1971, she joined the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) serving in various capaci- ties until her appointment as its Executive Director in 1987. on her ap- pointment, Dr. Sadik was one of the highest ranking women in the UN system and was the fi rst woman in the history of the United Nations, to be appointed to head one of its major voluntarily-funded programmes. She is well-known for her dynamism and guiding force in the fi eld of in- ternational maternal and child health, reproductive and sexual health, including family planning. Currently, Dr. Sadik participates as a Board member/Trustee of several international and national foundations.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a2389bf7-d2f2-4767-930e-1baf79d3f2c0": {"__data__": {"id_": "a2389bf7-d2f2-4767-930e-1baf79d3f2c0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "47cacf22b355c0c983e5ae8c402439e0f08ae300b7d7dfdec8f4e9acd52b8271"}, "2": {"node_id": "11282b6a-3239-467b-8fde-c640838380d1", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d05f43fb0ed1782583aa1c6d2b21944008279023c0581c544c8ab7f4290a7384"}}, "hash": "3c7d786c8c0f757f152f6acafd5c313ef701d87d34a600f7629bec701064fbf1", "text": "Sadik participates as a Board member/Trustee of several international and national foundations. Among them are the UN Foundation, Asia Society, the In- ternational HIV/AIDS Alliance, Deutsche Stiftung Weltbevoelkerung (DSW), Pathfi nder Internation- al, The World Population Foundation (WPF), Population Action International (PAI), Nuclear Threat Initiative (NTI), International Center for Research on Women (ICRW), Engender Health (EH), and the Women\u2019s Environment and Development organization (WEDo). PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS Chairpersons 6 established increased risk exposure to HIV be it through drug use or unprotected commercial sex (coerced sex for particularly vulnerable female migrant workers in some instances). Policies and programme interventions fall short of what is needed despite the millions of people concerned. \u2022\ufffd Interventions must cover male-to-male sexual contact in all its varieties as well as sexual contact among drug injectors, who may", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a7b64abc-313a-424e-810a-34f8573a8b4b": {"__data__": {"id_": "a7b64abc-313a-424e-810a-34f8573a8b4b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a0615ddff843b1eff3a0f0716bc8bed573b39136dd2ec11d4c5b2e290acec67e"}, "3": {"node_id": "6bd8a96c-080f-46ea-895a-64b4c1dd1672", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "cb82e05cfa7d71b04e25c92db6a0d3b3f569b742eafe09bae880e679e94c9020"}}, "hash": "abf25b478c7ad02b0016d958e85dc73bdfe89d23f3cf88ba988a1e35c979974a", "text": "already have acquired HIV by sharing contaminated needles. As the Commission on AIDS report (2008) notes, \u201cIf sustained, effective programmes to curb HIV trans- mission in commercial sex, drug injection, and male-male sex are established, countries will see a steady decrease in spousal transmission\u201d \u2022\ufffd Effective protection for women calls for programmes far beyond efforts made so far, which have concentrated on remedial approaches at home, providing shelter for women who fear or suffer vio- lence, or economic empowerment that at least offers women some independence. However, the root causes are still to be addressed. This requires a slew of activities, but, most important, social behavioral change and transformation. \u2022\ufffd National policies that support the many women who fear, or are actually suffering emotional or physical violence, including coerced sex within marriage, are needed. National legal frameworks are poorly enforced and family networks offer little support to the sufferer. Sometimes the woman who is the victim is even condemned. \u2022\ufffd Voluntary counseling and testing, and prevention of mother-to-child transmission services should be available at all sexual and reproductive health facilities. They should use expertise and experi- ence gained in family planning and reproductive health programmes. But they must also reach those who are not covered by these programmes - the unmarried, young couples who haven\u2019t had children, and men. The e-participants felt that compulsory HIV testing before marriage would be ineffective, because it does not address the main problem \u2013 that is, spousal behaviour post mar- riage. \u2022\ufffd Most participants felt that countries must eventually address the underlying power structures that effectively keep women in subjugation. As part of this approach, women need wider social and economic measures to empower them to take their lives into their own hands. \u2022\ufffd Research in Kerala, India, (also quoted in the AIDS Commission\u2019s report) is showing that 49 per cent of women with no property reported physical violence compared to only 7 per cent of women who owned property. \u2022\ufffd Women and girls need more and better general education on a par with men and boys. They need specific education on their sexual health and on ways to avoid sexually transmitted infections, in- cluding HIV. And they need the means to put their knowledge into practice. \u2022\ufffd Education and services must include sex workers. Such an approach involves tackling stigma and discrimination against them and their work. The whole area of commercial sex must be brought out in the open and frankly discussed. Educational outreach on sexual and reproductive health must include men and boys, specifically teaching them respect and consideration for women, in general, and their partners, in particular. \u2022\ufffd The final point emerging from the e-discussion is that infected women and their children need much more than care and treatment. They need real protection from stigma and discrimination. Such is the state of ignorance and prejudice that women are often blamed, quite unfairly, for infect- ing their husbands, when the reality is often the other way round. Their children may be excluded from school and from health services. Women also need economic empowerment. \u2018AIDS widows\u2019 are often denied their inheritance. Some have found themselves on the streets, shunned by their husbands\u2019 families. The law is on their side; but very few have the resources or the social support to seek legal redress. With empowerment, HIV positive women have become powerful advocates for change. Concluding, Dr. Nafis Sadik called for an open, frank and value-free discussion that shall reach every vil- lage and street, and informs policy and enforcement agencies from the highest level to the individual. PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS 7 PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS Prasada Rao, is the Director of the UNAIDS Regional Support Team, Asia and the Pacific. From 1997 to 2002, he was the Director of Indian National AIDS Control organisation (NACo). Among other initiatives, he devised and put into operation a national level sentinel surveillance system for tracking the epidemic which was the first of its kind in Asia and the Pacific. As Secretary for Health and Family Welfare Depart- ments, he was instrumental in drafting the National AIDS Prevention and Control Policy and the National Blood Transfusion Policy of India.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6bd8a96c-080f-46ea-895a-64b4c1dd1672": {"__data__": {"id_": "6bd8a96c-080f-46ea-895a-64b4c1dd1672", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a0615ddff843b1eff3a0f0716bc8bed573b39136dd2ec11d4c5b2e290acec67e"}, "2": {"node_id": "a7b64abc-313a-424e-810a-34f8573a8b4b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "abf25b478c7ad02b0016d958e85dc73bdfe89d23f3cf88ba988a1e35c979974a"}}, "hash": "cb82e05cfa7d71b04e25c92db6a0d3b3f569b742eafe09bae880e679e94c