ere is an urgency to find solutions for each specific context\u201d 8 PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS Dr Nafsiah Mboi, a Pediatrician and Master of Public Health by training, has been active in the field of HIV and AIDS since its first appearance in Indonesia. She presently serves as Secretary of the National AIDS Com- mission, a position to which she was appointed by the President of In- donesia in 2006. Dr Nafsiah has had a lengthy career of public service. For 35 years she was a civil servant with the Ministry of Health. Thereafter she served one term in the Indonesian Parliament. She later joined the World Health organization as Director of the Department of Gender and Women\u2019s Health. In addition to her professional career, Dr Nafsiah has been active through the years on a voluntary basis having founded and led a succession of community organizations in a range of fields includ- ing, family planning, social welfare, women\u2019s economic advancement, and rural family welfare. In addition to to serving in a number of national commissions, she has served as chair of the UN Com- mission on the Rights of the Child and Vice Chair of the Global Commission on Women\u2019s Health prior to that. The Challenges of Engendering National AIDS Programmes Including Low Risk Women Research in Indonesia In 2006, a mapping exercise on high-risk behaviour populations and their partners in Indonesia found that while Injecting Drug Users represented 46 per cent of the \u201cat-risk population\u201d, their partners com- prised 7 per cent. Similarly, there were significant numbers of partners of other \u201cat-risk groups\u201d such as clients of sex workers and Men who have Sex with Men (MSM). Focus on Evidence-Based Policy First, there is a need to integrate gender, reproductive rights and HIV throughout policy related to education as well as the workplace. Decriminalization of sex work is very important from the perspec- tive of prevention programmes, and in achieving 100 per cent condom use. We need explicit policy response for gender-based violence. We also need to scale up prevention of mother-to-child transmis- sion (PMTCT) programmes, and make data as the basis for policy and programmes. \u201cAlthough the number of at-risk women compared to men was small for the data collected in 2006, we found in our projections to the year 2020 that the proportion of women, both sex workers and others, would grow rapidly.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6a26ef41-752f-41cd-97ea-2bf4b5fb6413": {"__data__": {"id_": "6a26ef41-752f-41cd-97ea-2bf4b5fb6413", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "09eb302e8031ed2e4adaa0e3a09fd9873a67b67dd18957fe5bf02ffadb5d09ae"}, "2": {"node_id": "88c4a178-36eb-4e37-9b5d-e3ed778c8e01", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f53f027d300a130d0b75fa6ebca51743a582267e7d3b16adb7898e34ff0566f3"}}, "hash": "689b905929e9e727a07991e31c96e8c92bc5bc472a34c0a0b99f69d78dd9ec3e", "text": "This growing impact on women became evident and therefore there is a need to focus a lot more on women in our response\u201d Training & Education towards Behavioural Change More specific and explicit information and skill-training programmes are needed on managing rela- tionships and on responsible sex, giving priority to adolescents and married couples. We need to incor- porate e-learning tools in our training programmes to reach as", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c3b5c9fc-d113-482c-b319-bb06391af950": {"__data__": {"id_": "c3b5c9fc-d113-482c-b319-bb06391af950", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d1e9981c38c0ee83c671856fe8d5e98a96f8bd79ce3a5b0f01f2017e8917a17c"}}, "hash": "d1e9981c38c0ee83c671856fe8d5e98a96f8bd79ce3a5b0f01f2017e8917a17c", "text": "many young people as possible. We also Panelist Presentations 9 need to train and re-train our behavioural change counselors and Voluntary Counseling and Testing counselors, especially focusing on couples counseling. Promoting Condom-Use We also need to educate and involve stakeholders in condom-use campaigns \u2013 both in terms of com- mercial sex and longer-term relationships. It is very important to have the buy-in of local governments and policy-makers as well as pimps for eff ective condom promotion among clients of sex workers. We need to take this approach because all along we have only propagated condom-use among sex work- ers, and not to their clients. We also need to carry out periodic and systematic legal review and reform. Need for More Research We need to undertake more rigorous research because strategic choices are not possible without hard data. We need full epidemiological analysis of HIV and AIDS and projections as to who will be most at risk. Social research plays a crucial role in telling us what works in our setting and what empowers people for change. This includes sex workers, adolescents, police, clients of sex workers and so on. Delivering Key Messages Finally, we need public leadership to acknowledge, challenge and publicly embrace gender and rights- based approaches. We need to empower our men and women to take on new roles in relationships. We also need strong partnerships between health and community systems. We need to bear in mind the crucial factor of culture, and use culturally popular methods to deliver new messages. PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS 0 20,000 40,000 60,000 80,000 100,000 120,000 140,000 160,000 180,000 1989 1991 1993 1995 1997 1999 2001 2003 2005 2007 2009 2011 2013 2015 2017 2019 Primary Targets: Key Populations Most at Risk - Indonesia Proportions among new infections. Epidemiological modeling 1999 - 2020 Partner of FSW-Client Female Sex Worker MSM IDUs Client FSW New infections Source: Dr. Nafsiah Mboi PowerPoint Presentation, 11 Aug. 2009, ICAAP IX 10 PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS Men Women 75 million Men in Asia visit sex workers (2-20% of adult men) 50 million Women married to men who visit sex workers 1 million infants and children 10 million Men who inject drugs 10 million Women sell sex 10 million Men who have sex with men Migrants? Source: Commission on AIDS in Asia, 2008 Caitlin Wiesen-Antin is currently the UNDP Regional HIV/AIDS Practice Leader & Programme Coordinator for Asia and the Pacifi c, placed with the UNDP Regional Center in Colombo, Sri Lanka. She has over 20 years of development experience on issues relating to HIV/AIDS, gender and poverty in both Africa and Asia and has extensive experience in work- ing with civil society groups. Prior to her current assignment in the Asia and the Pacifi c, she held the positions of Senior Poverty and HIV Advi- sor for Africa and Director of the Civil Society Division at UNDP. Introduction to Intimate Partner Transmission in the Asian Region Another key dimension to the multiple linkages that exist between communities that are high at risk of HIV is migration. There are many men and women who migrate, get infected, and return home, which is an important factor in leading to risk of HIV infection in the region. The Increasing Risk Faced by Women in the Region As highlighted earlier, unprotected paid sex is the main driver of HIV epidemics in Asia. Three out of four adults living with HIV in Asia are men, yet the proportion of women living with HIV has increased from 19 per cent in 2000 to 24 per cent in 2007. The data are even more alarming for countries such as Thai- land where women account for 35 per cent of the infections, as well as Cambodia (47 per cent), India (37 per cent), and Papua New Guinea (60 per cent). In Thailand, a third of new infections are among women, and 70 per cent of infections among youth between 15 and 24 years are among women and girls. Ac- cording to the Commission on AIDS in Asia there are an estimated 50 million women who are at risk and vulnerable to infection from their partners who engage in high risk behaviors such as unprotected paid sex and injecting drug use and unprotected sex between men. 11 PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS The Effects of Migration Another population group that is highly at risk of HIV infection is the \u2018mobile\u2019 men who travel for work. A 2006 study conducted by Family Health International showed that this group is much more likely to engage in paid sex than men within the general population. In China, Cambodia", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a8af4374-c52d-4a2b-a404-d18076e9ff13": {"__data__": {"id_": "a8af4374-c52d-4a2b-a404-d18076e9ff13", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9e67bf1dcd9f760a55f1690ed898d9e02de425f206aaf92b1ee844375b6443b1"}, "3": {"node_id": "45ea1644-a519-4003-a45b-d733688b195c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a0e9eb53b31a996255ce0fe00f674e0d1f96ae443a1bb5cc446419767c4091ae"}}, "hash": "a64513ca3b24398fdc7b3cbb5e0252a273563028f29449a112e6936d9c818a7c", "text": "and Vietnam, where the study was conducted, over 30 per cent of \u201cmobile men\u201d engaged in sex with a sex worker. Source: Family Health International, 2006 General male population High risk & mobile occupations (truck drivers, fshermen, ...) China Cambodia Indonesia Viet Nam 35% 30% 25% 20% 15% 10% 5% 0% 9% 33% 15% 33% 4% 21% 2% 32% other studies have also shown that the longer men stay away from home, the more vulnerable to infec- tion they become. one study showed that HIV prevalence among migrant men increased from 2.5 per cent for those away from home for less than five years, to 8.5 per cent for those away from home for more than five years. \u201cMigrant women also face extraordinarily high risk of infection, especially those who migrate for domestic work. They often end up in very exploitative and abusive situations that put them in extreme risk for vulnerability to HIV\u201d Unsafe migration can lead to situations where women are trafficked and exploited. While human traf- ficking takes many forms, trafficking of women and girls for purposes of sexual exploitation remains the overwhelming dominant form of trafficking. Sexual exploitation, powerlessness, and inability to negotiate safe sex make women and girls vulnerable to HIV infection. Studies have shown that the rate of HIV infection is higher in younger women who were trafficked and sexually exploited. Nearly 60 per cent of women and girls who were trafficked in Nepal between the ages of 7 and 14 had contracted HIV infection, according to a 2007 study conducted by Jay Silverman of the Harvard School of Public Health. The study looked at the different gender norms that sanction violence against women, and cre- ates extraordinary vulnerability to sexual abuse and exploitation. The Gender Equation A country study undertaken in China on the impact of HIV and AIDS on marriage and households showed that the percentage of HIV-infected widows is much higher than widowers. More men are being infected at the outset and in turn are in turn infecting their spouses. As a result many men are dying early, leaving the burden of care and support for the family to their HIV positive spouses. Crucial to maintaining sero-discordancy among couples where one partner is HIV postiive and the other nega- tive and thereby halting the transmission of HIV in intimate partner relationships is the issue of early 12 PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS disclosure of HIV status. A study from China on the issue of disclosure in sero-discordant couples clearly showed a trend where women tend to disclose their HIV status earlier than men. In India, evidence shows that women are being largely infected by their husbands, and widows are most likely to have contracted HIV from their husbands. Nevertheless, as shown by another study in India, 80 per cent of HIV widows were denied a share of their husband\u2019s property, and when their hus- bands died they were pushed out of their marital homes often with their children and left to fend for themselves. Prevention Priorities The Commission on AIDS in Asia report concluded that prevention priorities in Asia were not strong enough, and that, \u201cat present, there is no effective strategy to protect women within marriage or steady relationship on a large scale. There is a need for high quality research for designing prevention pro- grammes for these populations\u201d. Recommendations A joint UNAIDS, UNDP,UNIFEM, ASEAN Foundation publication was released at ICAAP, detailing a frame- work for addressing intimate partner transmission. The framework advocates the following measures: \u2022\ufffd Income support for HIV positive women \u2022\ufffd Livelihood security for widows and affected families \u2022\ufffd Secure property and inheritance rights for women \u2022\ufffd Health insurance to protect against catastrophic health expenditures A publication was released this morning, detailing a framework for addressing intimate partner trans- mission. The framework includes the following: \u2022\ufffd Integrating the protection of women into HIV prevention programmes \u2022\ufffd Scaling up of prevention for MSM, IDU, clients of sex workers, and stressing on the protection of their female partners \u2022\ufffd Scaling up of prevention among mobile populations and migrants and focusing on protecting their intimate partners \u2022\ufffd Structural interventions for vulnerable women and their male sexual partners \u2022\ufffd Prioritizing operations research to deepen our understanding Paramount to effective interventions, it is critical for us to have costing that counts and to ensure that women-focused interventions are included and budgeted in national development strategies, plans and programmes and translated into action on the ground.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "45ea1644-a519-4003-a45b-d733688b195c": {"__data__": {"id_": "45ea1644-a519-4003-a45b-d733688b195c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9e67bf1dcd9f760a55f1690ed898d9e02de425f206aaf92b1ee844375b6443b1"}, "2": {"node_id": "a8af4374-c52d-4a2b-a404-d18076e9ff13", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a64513ca3b24398fdc7b3cbb5e0252a273563028f29449a112e6936d9c818a7c"}}, "hash": "a0e9eb53b31a996255ce0fe00f674e0d1f96ae443a1bb5cc446419767c4091ae", "text": "13 PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS How Do Positive Women See Intimate Partner Transmission? (Five key recommendations from the Women\u2019s and Lesbian Forum) More Awareness and Gender", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0caa0264-326c-4cc6-85d0-2ab6cb127beb": {"__data__": {"id_": "0caa0264-326c-4cc6-85d0-2ab6cb127beb", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4ef60f4a2307cc635d4072af402523a49f0829260abd5c8d974264e0822e8212"}, "3": {"node_id": "e62b4861-d707-4ee8-8ef5-7e3fbf8e4a1e", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fd885e5a7f1f8920e5c918ad85c1fd3b0b5998c44bbb9586d84771458d0205f4"}}, "hash": "60e017a673ede1b97fb575c09ee3dd84ed1c19e943af97f8545f62c28aa21c65", "text": "Responsive Action All actors involved in the response, that is, the UN, donors, civil society, local and international organiza- tions, government agencies and decision-makers, need to promote and implement gender-responsive policies and programmes. We need more gender responsive programmes that include the involvement of women in identifying, prioritizing and resolving reproductive health issues. We should include wom- en at policy-making levels and empower them to change their status within their home and the com- munity through income generation and political participation. Encourage Partnerships in Advancing Equality to Promote Gender Equity There are many inequalities that women face, such as in accessing basic facilities and opportunities, inequalities at the workplace, within households, and in inheritance and property ownership as high- lighted earlier. Policies should be in place for law enforcement and legal agencies to support women who are victims of violence including marital rape. \u201cWe should encourage more partnerships in advancing equality to promote gender equity. There should be better communication in partnerships be- tween men and women\u201d Equity and Rights We recommend educating and practicing of gender equity, and sexual health and rights values at the individual and family level. This includes understanding the sexual needs of HIV-positive women. Ac- cording to research, persons at the household level, that is, women, are most affected by the HIV epi- demic. Women carry the burden because they are the caregivers and surviving spouses. Therefore, we recommend that educating and practicing gender equity should start at the family level, which is the starting point of communities. Access to Comprehensive Services Comprehensive services include family planning, infertility treatment, safe abortion, choice of contra- ceptives, diagnosis and treatment of STI and HIV, pregnancy, cancer, PMTCT services, youth counseling, and safer sex services including for lesbians. Caroline Thomas is an HIV and AIDS advocate and activist with the SPIRITIA Foundation. She provides assistance to local and regional Indonesian HIV institutions in the areas of AIDS awareness, network development, access to treatment, emergency support and income generation for people living with HIV. Ms Thomas has extensive exper- tise on training and peer support programmes. She holds a degree in Psychology and is currently enrolled in a Master of Public Health pro- gramme. 14 PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS Geeta Rao Gupta is president of the International Center for Research on Women (ICRW). An internationally renowned expert on gender and development, Rao Gupta has more than 20 years of experience in women\u2019s health and is a leading global authority on women\u2019s role in development programs. She has expertise in gender mainstreaming in development; women\u2019s health; HIV and AIDS; women\u2019s economic em- powerment; private sector roles in development; strategies to empow- er women and advance gender equality; women and poverty. Geeta Rao Gupta has been president of ICRW since 1997. Rao Gupta served as co-chair of the U.N. Secretary General\u2019s High Level Panel on Youth Employment and cochaired the U.N. Millennium Project\u2019s Task Force on Promoting Gender Equal- ity and Empowering Women from 2002-2005. She also serves as an advisor to the UNAIDS Glob- al Coalition on Women and AIDS. Rao Gupta was the recipient of the 2007 Washington Business Journal\u2019s \u201cWomen Who Mean Business\u201d award and is frequently recognized for her commitment to quality research and dedication to the protection and fulfillment of women\u2019s human rights. The Gender Dimensions of HIV Transmission in Intimate Partner Relationships A Note on the Terminology While I recognize that a lot of thought has gone into the terminology of \u201cIntimate Partner Transmission\u201d, we need to be careful of not over-generalizing terms when we define problems broadly, as this may lead to ineffective solutions. We need to be clear about the exact problem we are grappling with in dif- ferent contexts, and then develop solutions to address them specifically. The recognition of what we call \u201cIntimate Partner Transmission\u201d should underscore for us the need to continue to do what we are already doing, that is, directing our resources to those who are most-at-risk. It is the infection among those most-at-risk that are being transmitted into long-term intimate partner- ships. But in order to succeed in breaking that link, we must augment what we have been doing with what we knew must have been done all along.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e62b4861-d707-4ee8-8ef5-7e3fbf8e4a1e": {"__data__": {"id_": "e62b4861-d707-4ee8-8ef5-7e3fbf8e4a1e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4ef60f4a2307cc635d4072af402523a49f0829260abd5c8d974264e0822e8212"}, "2": {"node_id": "0caa0264-326c-4cc6-85d0-2ab6cb127beb", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "60e017a673ede1b97fb575c09ee3dd84ed1c19e943af97f8545f62c28aa21c65"}}, "hash": "fd885e5a7f1f8920e5c918ad85c1fd3b0b5998c44bbb9586d84771458d0205f4", "text": "\u201cWe need to address the underlying structural causes that put particular populations at risk and increase the vulnerability of women in long-term, stable, sexual partnerships. By addressing these structural factors we will greatly increase the effectiveness of our efforts to reduce the risk faced by sex workers, MSMs, and IDUs, and break the link between their risk and that of their regular partners\u201d Stronger and Wider", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f3c3553c-c54f-428d-9781-7b020923ee73": {"__data__": {"id_": "f3c3553c-c54f-428d-9781-7b020923ee73", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "016e8ab6827d071042a9663f38c78fe334c9b4958a8f5330ba605c29b97e4453"}, "3": {"node_id": "2645cbdb-c108-49f5-8787-7d0ce3695fe2", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f5b4a6fc2668f2847f35a987020d917be862d1392d05b90938bc75fd6fe8b467"}}, "hash": "4391a87f9adf12ad03dda68628c49a8282a4e6f1f3a95c200c9eb06071ce33e5", "text": "Networks and Partnerships \u201cWe should strengthen the networking between positive women and rights organizations across the Asia-Pacific region. We need better public leader- ship, more empowerment and stronger partnerships\u201d 15 PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS Three Structural Factors Fuelling Intimate Partner Transmission There are three fundamental gender-related structural factors that interact to fuel intimate partner transmission. The first is gender inequality in access to productive resources, an inequality that favors men and creates an unequal balance of power in heterosexual relationships. This inequality makes it less likely that women will have control over sexual interactions and make them more prone to be vic- tims of domestic violence. It also makes them less likely to be able to negotiate condom use or fidelity in their relationships, or leave relationships that they perceive to be risky. Moreover, when women marry young and marry men older than them, a demographic pattern that is fairly common in this region, that power imbalance is further exacerbated, making young women even more vulnerable to becoming infected from their partners. The second factor that fuels Intimate Partner Transmission is the prevalent sexual norms that promote a hetero-normative view of male and female sexuality. This stigmatizes homosexuality and bisexuality, and upholds a double standard of appropriate sexual behavior. The stigma associated with homosexu- ality and bisexuality forces men who have sex with men to keep their sexual behavior and sexual prefer- ences hidden, and adhere to the social pressure to prove their heterosexuality by marrying unsuspect- ing women. Similarly, it is the criminalization and stigmatization of sex workers that put them at greater risk of physical and sexual violence, and forces them to go underground or disperse into settings where it is difficult to reach them or provide health services. The stigma and criminalization also drive their male clients underground, making it difficult to reach them with HIV-prevention education. In all of these ways prevalent sexual norms conspire to create the grounds for Intimate Partner Transmission. The third structural factor that feeds women\u2019s vulnerability in long-term relationships in Asia is the culture of silence that shrouds sex and sexuality, despite more than two decades of exposure to the HIV virus. It is this culture that creates the dichotomy of casual sex as compared to intimate partner sex. Casual sex is socially structured as furtive, free of social boundaries and thus, satisfying, while intimate partner sex is structured as obligatory, stable, for purposes of procreation and, thus, not exciting. It is this culture that keeps women uninformed about sex and HIV prevention, apart from restricting inter- partner communication on ways to make sex more satisfying and pleasurable. A Paradigm Shift \u201cWe cannot hope to address this problem only through public health mea- sures. We need to shift the dynamic of gender relations\u201d Community-based initiatives that address damaging norms of masculinity and femininity and reduce the acceptability of violence against women must be supported and scaled up. Simultaneously, we must implement legislative, policy and programmatic measures to promote gender equality and the empowerment of women and girls. These should include the enforcement of laws to grant women equal property and inheritance rights and allow them to make independent decisions regarding mar- riage and divorce. We should also work towards policies that increase women\u2019s access to economic op- portunities and formal employment. We should step up efforts to ensure that girls complete secondary education and have livelihood alternatives, and put in place programmes to increase women\u2019s access to sexual and reproductive health services. \u201cOnce women have more choices to earn an income, to move freely, to de- cide if and when to have sex and get married, and when men realize the cost of perpetuating inequality and damaging norms of masculinity, then reduc- tions in long-term intimate partner transmission will follow\u201d 16 PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS Rufino \u201cRaffy\u201d Martinez is a Migrant Health advocate with ACHIEVE Inc. and a graduate of the Philippine Maritime Institute. As a seafarer him- self he has circumnavigated the world. Raffy has been involved in HIV prevention and education projects for many years and supports NGo initiatives as a volunteer resource person and trainer for HIV Pre-Depar- ture orientation Seminar for seafarers. Raffy has deep knowledge and understanding of migrant health issues in the region, in particular the situation faced by seafarers.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2645cbdb-c108-49f5-8787-7d0ce3695fe2": {"__data__": {"id_": "2645cbdb-c108-49f5-8787-7d0ce3695fe2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "016e8ab6827d071042a9663f38c78fe334c9b4958a8f5330ba605c29b97e4453"}, "2": {"node_id": "f3c3553c-c54f-428d-9781-7b020923ee73", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4391a87f9adf12ad03dda68628c49a8282a4e6f1f3a95c200c9eb06071ce33e5"}}, "hash": "f5b4a6fc2668f2847f35a987020d917be862d1392d05b90938bc75fd6fe8b467", "text": "Mobility, Families and HIV Vulnerability: A Personal Testimony Migrant Experience I am Raffy Martinez, 38 years old, and married with two children. I worked eight years in a shipping company and my last job was in 2003. After my arrival in the Philippines, I underwent surgery for a hemorrhage and was diagnosed with", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "10340f39-cf32-4bc4-9f8c-07d5d4352fcb": {"__data__": {"id_": "10340f39-cf32-4bc4-9f8c-07d5d4352fcb", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1d0bcb2bc5c5b024b19ec5970d751d67267bdafea2b668cddbabeb56fef49024"}}, "hash": "1d0bcb2bc5c5b024b19ec5970d751d67267bdafea2b668cddbabeb56fef49024", "text": "TB. I was on medication for eight months, but I thought everything would be fine once I recovered. But it was not. I was diagnosed with HIV. Although it was difficult, I told my wife about my infection. After a long explanation everything was settled. I encouraged her to have a test done for HIV but she refused to do so. In her mind, she already had the virus. She was also worried about the potential social and health consequences of being infected, including the future of our children. At that time, free ARV treatment was not available for people living with HIV. The pre-departure orientation sessions conducted by my employer did not include HIV/AIDS orientation. We travel far from our loved ones, and tend to engage in sexual encounters with other women and with men. We are also subject to peer pressure to engage in such activity, especially when the ship is in port. There are also negative attitudes with respect to condom-use. Seafarers are largely unaware of the risk that they expose themselves and their loved ones to. Four years after my diagnosis, my wife decided to undergo an HIV test. The availability of ARV through the Global Fund programme, and the help of positive commu- nity networks, NGOs, Government, and other stakeholders made her realize that it was important to get tested. She also tested positive. Migrant workers returning home do not choose to undergo voluntary testing. This is important to ensure that the migrant knows his status, and so he can save himself from infectious diseases. Spouses left behind by their husbands remain faithful. Most spouses don\u2019t think they can get infected with HIV because of the belief that only sex workers can get HIV/AIDS. Finally, the spouses don\u2019t know that if they are already infected with HIV, mother-to-child transmission is Meanwhile, we must continue to work towards reducing the vulnerability of most-at-risk populations, including decriminalizing sex work and homosexuality. These measures will help to reduce the risk of these populations apart from helping to reduce stigma and fostering openness about sexual identity and sexual practice. We must continue to push for age-appropriate sex education for children and ado- lescents, and facilitate open, community led discussions of sexuality, while simultaneously sponsoring new research that will demystify the sexual lives and identities of women and men. With all of these measures, we will be able to dismantle the foundation of inequality, fight the stigma, and break the silence on which intimate partner transmission thrives. 17 PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS Anandi Yuvaraj is Asia-Pacific regional coordinator for the Internation- al Community of Women Living with HIV/AIDS (ICW). She previously served as programme manager for HIV and Sexual Reproductive Health at PATH\u2019s India office. She has played a vital role in broadening politi- cal and social responses to the epidemic in India and abrove Through her participation in various international fora that address the involve- ment of people living with HIV, she has been instrumental in mobilising communities to raise their voices, call attention to their needs and con- cerns, and build supportive environments. Currently, Ms. Yuvaraj pro- vides technical support to the India Campaign for Microbicides and the Indian National AIDS Control organisation on the Greater Involvement of People Living with and Directly Affected by HIV/AIDS. She is also a member of a number of other national advisory boards including the Indian chapter of the International AIDS Vaccine Initiative and the Indian Council of Medical Research. Discussant MS. Anandi Yuvaraj took questions and remarks from the floor and led a brief discussion between the panelists and the floor on the need to develop responses that are beyond the current scope of inter- ventions, addressing in particular the structural drivers of Intimate Partner Transmission in the region. She recalled some of the key issues as well as opportunities highlighted throughout the presentations. The following pages present a comprehensive account of the challenges raised during the symposium and key recommendations proposed. possible. I would like to call upon migrants to be vigilant and to think several times before engaging in activi- ties that put themselves and their families at risk. Some of the consequences that I faced after testing positive are that I am not able to work abroad due to compulsory medical testing by companies; and I find it difficult to support the education, housing and other needs of my family. I also experience low morale and poor self- esteem due to my HIV positive status. \u201cThus, I am calling on government agencies, NGOs and other institutions such as the UN, the WHO, and the Global Fund", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "859ba7ba-2d16-4fa4-bf3f-e0f2c8ad43a0": {"__data__": {"id_": "859ba7ba-2d16-4fa4-bf3f-e0f2c8ad43a0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "205bdd9b7abefda4511b880540a38b52b63a06b8be930601c5b7c8c796a6520f"}}, "hash": "205bdd9b7abefda4511b880540a38b52b63a06b8be930601c5b7c8c796a6520f", "text": "to support reintegration programmes for returning HIV positive migrant workers, as well as provide them sustained access to treatment, care and support. I also call for greater involvement of People Living with HIV in HIV-related programmes\u201d 18 PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS Key Challenges \u2022\ufffd The issue of intimate partner transmission of HIV has not yet gained tradition in the strategies and policies of national governments in the region despite evidence from the field showing its growing importance; \u2022\ufffd At present, there is no effective strategy to protect women within marriage. There exists a huge gap in the understanding of the characteristics of sexual behaviour among intimate partners that render the designing of effective prevention programmes difficult; \u2022\ufffd The strong patriarchal culture in Asian countries severely limits a woman\u2019s ability to negotiate sex in intimate partner relationships; \u2022\ufffd HIV prevention programmes focused on female partners of men with high-risk behaviors have still not found a place in national HIV plans and priorities; \u2022\ufffd Interventions that only focus on the behaviours and do not address the structural context that shape these behaviours are likely to fail; \u2022\ufffd It is important to understand why men seek paid sex. In this context, it is also important to under- stand the sexual behaviours of migrant workers. While there is no or very little research on this, it could be speculated that seeking paid sex gives them a sense of control which they lack in their daily lives; \u2022\ufffd Violence \u2013 intimate partner violence in particular - and HIV risk have a number of critical intersec- tions. While forced sex poses a direct biological risk for HIV, intimate partner violence also poses in- direct risks, by for example limiting one\u2019s ability to refuse sex or negotiate safe sex, and violence, or the fear of it, may deter women from disclosing their HIV status or seeking HIV testing. This brings to the fore the issue of gender inequality; \u2022\ufffd This also brings into focus the need to address the underlying power structures that effectively keep women in subjugation. As part of this effort, women need wider social and economic mea- sures that would empower them to take their lives in their own hands. This is an area that remains largely under-served; \u2022\ufffd The infected women and children need much more than care and treatment. Importantly, they need protection from stigma and discrimination. There is an urgent need to have an open, frank and value-free discussion on this issue that reaches every person, including in remote corners of the countries in the region, and informs policy-makers and enforcement agencies; \u2022\ufffd The current efforts to address the issue are only remedial. There is a need for programmes to go far beyond these and address structural interventions that are the key to making a dent in the factors underlying the growth of intimate partner transmission of HIV. 19 PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS Key Recommendations A Framework to Address Intimate Partner Transmission of HIV A framework to address HIV transmission in Intimate Partner Transmission in Asia is urgently needed. The framework needs to be both strategic and comprehensive. Critical in this framework is a strong cross-collaboration among actors and the need for a long-term vision. The coverage of populations is an important factor. In most Asian countries, the coverage levels of HIV prevention programmes are barely 30 per cent on an average and hence they hardly dent the progres- sion of the epidemic. Initial work undertaken in Asia highlights the need to incorporate protection for women into all HIV prevention programmes and the need for high quality research to deepen the understanding of the dynamics of HIV transmission among intimate partners prior to designing prevention programmes to address it. Key strategic interventions that have proved successful need to be significantly scaled up. In particular, interventions for MSM, IDUs and clients of sex workers; prevention programmes for \u201cmobile popula- tions\u201d and migrant workers with strong focus on protecting intimate partners. other interventions must include preventing intimate partner violence (including sexual violence), promoting gender equality, reducing income inequities across gender, promoting property rights for women, reducing vulnerability conditions in migration, reducing stigma and discrimination, and im- proving disclosure within discordant couples13. These interventions need to be supported by an enabling environment, hence the need to begin to address the structural determinants of Intimate Partner Transmission of HIV, such as profound gender inequality in law, custom and practice and unfavorable legal frameworks to address HIV comprehen- sively. The following suggestions are examples of measures, among others, that the panelists felt would con- tribute to reduce intimate partner transmission in Asia: More Gender-Responsive", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7e632a60-1435-461d-a018-4aa35103007d": {"__data__": {"id_": "7e632a60-1435-461d-a018-4aa35103007d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2393a306b1db0f173194ecd5f2622e2c7a54dc9d1eda1ca43864f0fb53f0d013"}, "3": {"node_id": "b399be97-ff56-4cb1-959e-a1343513b76b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fa64f1a8848e8dfdfa1dc391a48620b99072216d47446d100dee580a51ea7bec"}}, "hash": "50ee50f5a2a429c13c790855bd42714b832cf1437c3f1fa5016127f6eb0b8768", "text": "Action: There is a need to enhance gender-responsive action by all stakeholders including the UN, donors, lo- cal and international organizations, government agencies, enforcement agencies and decision-makers. Women-friendly income support programmes for HIV infected households; support for families car- ing for children orphaned by AIDS; review/develop/amend laws and policies to guarantee inheritance rights for women; care for the AIDS-affected should be included in the social security system; and fami- lies should be involved in the prevention of parent-to-child transmission. It is Important to provide women easy access to comprehensive sexual and reproductive health ser- vices14 and also make these services \u2018couple friendly\u2019. Gender and reproductive rights should be an in- tegral part of all HIV programmes and there should be an explicit policy on gender-based violence15. In certain contexts, the prevention of violence against women, girls, boys and sexual minorities should be an integral part of HIV prevention. In this context, it is important to have a periodic review of policies and reform of the legal systems that govern women and vulnerable populations, including the review of laws that criminalize sex work and homosexuality. 13 HIV Transmission in Intimate Partner Relationships in Asia, UNAIDS, 2009 14 Caroline Thomas, Women\u2019s Asia Pacific Network of Positive People (WAPN+), Indonesia 15 Dr. Nafsiah Mboi, Secretary National AIDS Commission, Indonesia 20 PANELIST PRESENTATIoNS AND STATEMENTS Addressing Underlying Structures: In order to support effective preventative measures and interventions, it is important to address the underlying structural causes that put women at risk and increase their vulnerability to HIV in long-term and stable sexual relationships. This will substantially enhance the effectiveness of the efforts to reduce the HIV risk of sex workers, MSM, and IDUs, and would also help break the link between their risk and that of their regular sexual partners. Legal frameworks that continue to pose significant challenges to universal access, prevention treat- ment and care need to be improved and integrate the gender equality and human rights obligations made by governments in line with their international commitments. Measures and programmes that promote and enhance women and girls\u2019 economic empowerment is another broad area of structural intervention that has proved determinant in decreasing women\u2019s vul- nerability to gender based violence and increasing their ability to negotiate safe sex. Community-based initiatives that address damaging norms of masculinity and femininity, promote positive models of masculinities among men and boys and reduce the acceptability of violence against women must be supported and scaled up. Similarly, it is critical to put in place a system to address the factors that make the migrants vulnerable to HIV throughout the migration process. A re-integration programme for migrant workers who are sent back from the host country after being infected with HIV should also be worked out16. Legislation preventing the movement of people who are HIV positive or that impose mandatory testing of future migrants need to be revised as they are ineffective, violate human rights and are not justified in public health. Enhancing Education, Training and Behavioural Change: While continuing to create conditions to lower the vulnerability of most-at-risk populations, there is a need to continue to push for age-appropriate sex education for children and adolescents, and facilitate open, community-led discussions on sexuality. Providing adolescents and married couples skill-train- ing programmes on managing relationships and information on responsible sex is important. There is a need to incorporate e-learning tools in all training programmes so as to reach as many young people as possible. There is also a need to train and re-train behavioral change counselors and VCT counselors, especially focusing on couple counseling. Promoting Condom-Use: As condoms remain the most effective HIV prevention intervention, there is a need to educate and involve all stakeholders in condom-use campaigns. Important in this is to have the buy-in of local gov- ernments, and policy-makers for effective condom promotion among clients of sex workers and among married couples. This approach is particularly important because so far efforts on condoms promotion have essentially targeted sex workers and not their clients. More Research: Quality and context specific research is the basis for making informed policy choices and design effec- tive interventions. There is need for more rigorous operational social research on the political economy of marriage and extramarital sex in the various Asian contexts and understand how this shapes HIV risk and how people could be empowered for change.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b399be97-ff56-4cb1-959e-a1343513b76b": {"__data__": {"id_": "b399be97-ff56-4cb1-959e-a1343513b76b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Intimate Partner Transmission: A Call for Action - Symposium Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2393a306b1db0f173194ecd5f2622e2c7a54dc9d1eda1ca43864f0fb53f0d013"}, "2": {"node_id": "7e632a60-1435-461d-a018-4aa35103007d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-intimate-partner-transmission-call-action-symposium-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "50ee50f5a2a429c13c790855bd42714b832cf1437c3f1fa5016127f6eb0b8768"}}, "hash": "fa64f1a8848e8dfdfa1dc391a48620b99072216d47446d100dee580a51ea7bec", "text": "Epidemiological analysis of HIV trends and projec- tions are also needed to keep track of the often changing trends of HIV epidemics and better target in- terventions. Research on challenges faced by sero-discordant couples, prevention methods and coping mechanisms is critical to design effective interventions", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "