hood security for widows and affected families, securing property and inheritance rights for women, health insurance and social protection mechanisms to protect against catastrophic health expenditures. Resource Needs Estimation Tools: There is need for new \u2018resource needs\u2019 estimation tools. Gender and human rights concerns are found in national AIDS strategies but are not often budgeted and therefore not translated into action. Thus, it is important to include the provision of an enabling environment, including human rights and gender dimensions to HIV responses, even while working out budgets17. Delivering Key Messages and Leadership: Public leadership is needed to acknowledge, challenge and publicly embrace gender transformative and rights-based approaches. There is a need to empower men and women to take on new roles in relationships. It is important to build strong partnerships between health and community systems and build a strong prevention advocacy community. It is crucial to recognize culture as an important factor and use culturally popular methods to deliver messages as well as for creating safe and secure spaces for women and girls and men and boys to discuss issues related to sexuality and build more HIV resilient communities. 17 Caitlin Wiesen, HIV Practice Team Leader, UNDP Regional Centre for Asia and the Pacific 22 RESoURCES References Commission on AIDS in Asia, 2008. Redefining AIDS in Asia: Crafting an Effective Response. Report of the Commission on AIDS in Asia. oxford University Press. Decker et al., 2009. Intimate partner violence is both a risk marker and a transmission mechanism for women\u2019s HIV infection: Findings from a national population-based sample of Indian husband-wife dyads. JAIDS. Family Health International, 2006. Protecting People on the Move: Applying Lessons Learned in Asia to Improve HIV/AIDS Interventions for Mobile People. International Centre for Research on Women, 2007. Engaging men and boys to achieve gende