s globally, reports an estimated 150,000 trafficking victims each year and has emerged as a source, destination, and transit area for trafficking in persons for both in-country and cross- border trafficking.8 Bangladesh, Nepal, and Sri Lanka are the major centres of origin, while India and Pakistan are destinations or transit countries to other regions, particularly the Middle East.9 Commercial sexual exploitation is the most virulent form of trafficking in South Asia, followed by trafficking for the purpose of forced labour. Other forms of human trafficking include forced marriage, domestic service, organized begging, camel racing, circus work, illicit adoption, pornography production, and organ trafficking. Most of those trafficked are women and girls, but men and boys are also trafficked, with boys as camel jockeys, for forced labour, for adoption, and in some areas as sex workers, and men for forced labour. Within South Asia, a large number of Nepali and Bangladeshi women are trafficked into India and Pakistan, most often as sex workers in the entertainment industry. In Bangladesh, Nepal, and Pakistan, adult women and children of both sexes are more frequently identified as trafficking victims. Trafficking in Nepal is primarily for sexual exploitation. Adult male trafficking victims were reported in Bangladesh, but often for 7 UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo, \u201dHuman Trafficking and HIV: Exploring vulnerabilities and responses in South Asia\u201d, 2007 8 The highest numbers are estimated to be 225,000 and come from South-East Asia according to the United Nations Population Fund, State of World Population 2006: A Passage to Hope \u2013 Women and International Migration, 2006. 9 Masud Ali, A. K. M., \u201cTreading along a Treacherous Trail: Research on Trafficking in Persons in South Asia,\u201d in Data and Research on Human Trafficking: A Global Survey, IOM, 2005. OVERVIEW 8 forced labour rather than sexual exploitation. A significant number of forced labour cases were reported in India from 2003 to 2006, with labour trafficking more frequent than trafficking for sexual exploitation. Migrants have been illegally smuggled into Europe and other countries from South Asia, often under hazardous conditions and under various guises.10 The common route to the Middle East and Europe from Bangladesh or Nepal is to transit through India or Pakistan, often utilizing Indian air routes. Trafficking from Bangladesh to India and Pakistan is via the main trafficking route: Dhaka-Mumbai-Karachi-Dubai. Conflict zones are known to be a haven for traffickers, as internal displacement and adverse human security conditions often lead to forced migration from these areas. In times of hardship, mobility may start out as undocumented migration for employment 10 United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime, \u201dResponding to Trafficking for Sexual Exploitation in South Asia,\u201d Regional Conference Report, October 2007; available at www.ungift.org/docs/ungift/pdf/world/INDIA.pdf. opportunities and end up as trafficking.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "64bec492-096b-4e42-b34c-1c06668882cb": {"__data__": {"id_": "64bec492-096b-4e42-b34c-1c06668882cb", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Mobility in South Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8d21e237e134b57ab52d98