n is separated from nearby Nepal by the Indian state of Sikkim, and in the south, it is separated from Bangladesh by West Bengal. The country\u2019s borders are porous, with thriving commerce and trade.2 Bhutan\u2019s per capita gross national income (GNI) is one of the highest in South Asia, and has consistently risen from US$730 in 2000 to US$1,900 in 2008.3 However, despite rapid economic growth and the signifi cant development eff orts of the Royal Government of Bhutan, about 25 percent of the population, mostly from rural areas, continue to live below the poverty line. Accordingly, the country\u2019s Tenth Five Year Plan (2008- 2013) has adopted poverty reduction as its overarching theme and primary goal.4 Migration Patterns Bhutan is largely a migrant-receiving country, reported in 2007 as hosting approximately 18,000 foreign workers.5 Outward migration in Bhutan is minimal, 1 National Statistical Bureau, Royal Government of Bhutan, 2005; available at www.bhutan.gov.bt/government/ aboutbhutan.php. 2 National Strategic Plan for the Prevention and Control of STIs and HIV and AIDS (NSP), Royal Government of Bhutan, 2008. 3 World Bank,\u201dBhutan - Country Overview,\u201d October 2009. 4 Gross National Happiness Commission, \u201cTenth Five Year Plan,\u201d Volume 1: Main Document, 2008-2013, Royal Government of Bhutan. 5 Labour Market Information Bulletin, Issue #2, Department of Employment, Ministry of Labour & Human Resources, 2007 45 and limited data is available on documented migrants.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e5743c82-2d46-43d3-8840-3ac10aa05fe9": {"__data__": {"id_": "e5743c82-2d46-43d3-8840-3ac10aa05fe9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Mobility in South Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b53232030ee0d288446081c2d43bc203e20e78d636d4d742044b2ce189daa42e"}, "2": {"node_id": "14e2cfbe-668e-4b7b-8067-e6fc01cb12f0", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e152e21e77597a0ae798020256d66db5a6609dde6f835fb74c80d81766e09284"}}, "hash": "77a67fc81e9b82260063b4f01d5ecaf40daef06ea462998976b33f7c93d88e53", "text": "Bhutanese leaving the country in search of work abroad are usually undocumented, but the number is still very small. The Labour Market Information Division under the Department of Employment has sole responsibility for conducting surveys and research on labour. Once their surveys are completed, Bhutan hopes to have detailed information on the diff erent categories of migrant workers. The Ministry of Labour and Human Resources (MoLHR) reported a national labour force of 249,030 individuals (158,073 male and 90,957 female) in 2005, of which 108,617 worked in the agricultural sector, with the next largest number working in the construction sector.6 Many who are classifi ed as \u201cemployed\u201d do not necessarily have a year-round job, but work seasonally, with little or no remuneration. The National Labour Force Survey 2006 shows labour force participation in urban areas at 57.2 percent, and is highest (73.3 percent) among the 45-49 age group. Labour force participation in rural areas is 63.5 percent, with the highest rate (82.8 percent) in the 35- 39 age group. There is active internal mobility, with the government reporting that, as of 2005, more than a sixth of the population had moved from rural villages to urban centres since birth.7 Approximately 20,000 people working as drivers and in private and public transport services have signifi cantly added to this rural- to-urban group.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e83a8b67-ff8a-4489-9f29-ea60bc5cc8f9": {"__data__": {"id_": "e83a8b67-ff8a-4489-9f29-ea60bc5cc8f9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Mobility in South Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6c36ff6c16358e5e2b1e0170d6f382f56b12192d68e35feb5491e1d57716267e"}, "3": {"node_id": "36c1ee10-1523-4795-afc9-6eca4fee99b4", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ec83c6193994cd599bb66b130b1f2cbcdf59f5eac8f7dd5b495b64ebf61e6225"}}, "hash": "0a16f2a3c06ed44b48a06098ad9536560709757ab4d994570e1bad5dea17ff87", "text": "With a booming construction industry adding nearly 30,000 skilled and unskilled workers every year, Bhutan is heavily dependent on a workforce imported largely from neighbouring India and Nepal.8 Approximately 3,000 local workers or expatriates are recruited to work as temporary daily labourers in the construction and production sectors. Migrant workers are engaged in various jobs within the services sector, and include professionals such as doctors, teachers/lecturers, as well as skilled workers and unskilled workers. However, many occupations have been closed to foreign workers since June 1, 2004. 6 Ministry of Labour and Human Resources, 2007. 7 National Population and Housing Census, 2005. 8 NSP, 2008. Table 1: List of occupations closed to foreign workers Accountant Typist/Clerk Computer Operator Driver Tour/Travel Guide Childcare Worker/ Housekeeper Messenger Tailor Gardener Offi ce Assistant Receptionist/Dispatcher Telephone Operator Administrative & Personnel Messenger Shop Salesperson Waiter/Waitress Security Guard/Watchman/ Caretaker Fitter/Plumber (except industrial fi tter) Hairdresser Source: Ministry of Labour and Human Resources, Royal Government of Bhutan. Gender and Migration In Bhutan, overall the participation rate of men in the labour force is higher (74.4 percent) than that of women (60.6 percent). Although the participation of women in the labour force has increased over the past fi ve years, household responsibilities, care of children, and work on the farm, together with their relative lack of education, have hampered women from accessing employment opportunities outside the home.9 Table 2: Gender Profi le of Mobile Populations 2007 Labour and Unemployment Rates Male Female Labour Force Participation Rate - Overall 74.4% 60.6% Labour Force Mobility \u2013 Rural to Urban 60.0% 40.0% Labour Force Participation Rate - Urban Areas 76.8% 41.5% Urban Unemployment Rate 3.6% 7.4% Source: Bhutan Living Standard Survey 2007 Analysis of mobility data reveals that 60 percent of internally mobile populations are men. Women moving to urban areas often fi nd employment as domestic helpers for the urban elite, particularly in childcare. Young girls engaged in this type of work often drop 9 \u201dBhutan Living Standard Survey 2007,\u201d National Statistics Bureau. BHUTAN 46 out of school, further limiting their future employment opportunities.10 Urbanization has led to increased financial pressures and unemployment, which has affected women more than men. According to census reports the urban unemployment rate is much higher for women (7.6 percent) than for men (3.6 percent).11 The linkages between migration and unemployment, poverty, and financial burdens are well established, and often lead to the increased labour migration of women \u2013 most often undocumented and unsafe. Reports on the status of women and children in Bhutan, particularly in rural areas, indicate that some women are abandoned by husbands who set off to find work elsewhere and never return.12 Lack of data makes it difficult to analyse the gender profile of migrants from Bhutan. An in-depth study focusing on the various factors and linkages associated with migration, including an assessment of the impact of male migration on the women and families left behind, would be useful in understanding the role of gender in migration patterns and trends. Human Trafficking Although official data regarding trafficking in women and young girls within or outside Bhutan is not available, there have been anecdotal reports of Bhutanese women and children in the sex market outside Bhutan, and fairly frequent reports of missing persons.13 Due to socio-economic progress and rapid modernization, the economic disparities between groups, regions, and sexes is widening, leading to increasing financial pressure on women and girls. As a result, many young girls from rural areas move to affluent urban areas in search of better opportunities and, once there, suffer from various forms of exploitation and human rights violations, including domestic violence, sexual exploitation, and forced sex work.14 Evidence of increasing commercial sex work in towns such as Phuentsholing and Thimpu has been reported. 10 National Commission for Women and Children, Royal Government of Bhutan, May 2007; National Plan of Action for Gender, 2008-2013, Gross National Happiness Commission, National Commission of Women and Children, Royal Government of Bhutan. 11 National Plan of Action for Gender, 2008-2013. 12 UNICEF,\u201dSituation Analysis of Children and Women in Bhutan,\u201d 2008. 13 National Plan of Action for Gender. 14 Ibid.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "36c1ee10-1523-4795-afc9-6eca4fee99b4": {"__data__": {"id_": "36c1ee10-1523-4795-afc9-6eca4fee99b4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Mobility in South Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6c36ff6c16358e5e2b1e0170d6f382f56b12192d68e35feb5491e1d57716267e"}, "2": {"node_id": "e83a8b67-ff8a-4489-9f29-ea60bc5cc8f9", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0a16f2a3c06ed44b48a06098ad9536560709757ab4d994570e1bad5dea17ff87"}}, "hash": "ec83c6193994cd599bb66b130b1f2cbcdf59f5eac8f7dd5b495b64ebf61e6225", "text": "13 National Plan of Action for Gender. 14 Ibid. The Health Mini