to 2007 * Emigration check not required 65 called secondary migration. Regarding student migration, five countries account for 90 percent of all Indian tertiary students abroad. The United States is by far the most important destination country, receiving more than half of worldwide expatriate Indian students in 2006-2007, followed by Australia at 16 percent, and the United Kingdom at 15 percent.28 Migrants to India According to the United Nations, India placed 8th in the world among countries hosting migrants from other nations in 2005.29 Neighbouring countries are the main source of international migrants in India, and this cross-border migration includes documented as well as undocumented migrants.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f5313d69-be18-4203-90b9-56443d2e504b": {"__data__": {"id_": "f5313d69-be18-4203-90b9-56443d2e504b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Mobility in South Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5574018dc7250a8897a55a72a0070c64ed491826696aea4c346428010a78c08d"}, "2": {"node_id": "8a9bfd27-d804-4190-8eab-f5d0eceb6643", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}