igrants. Content should include: information on HIV/AIDS; host country laws and customs; the rights of migrant workers; and the health services available to migrants. 10. Ensure policies and legislation are based on gender-sensitive, rights-based, and multisectoral approaches; and integrate migration issues with issues of HIV and AIDS while acknowledging the nexus between migration and human traffi cking by passing the pending International Migration Policy, the HIV Bill, and amendments to the ITPA. 11. Ensure comprehensive migrant-friendly voluntary HIV testing that protects the rights of both Indian migrants abroad and migrants in India in a process governed by best practices, i.e. informed consent, confi dentiality, and pre- and post-test counselling. 12. Protection of migrants from mandatory testing and deportation due to HIV status needs to be stated in existing and future bilateral agreements and MoU with labour receiving countries. This applies for Indian migrants going abroad as well as for migrants in India. 13. Ensure returning migrant workers, as well as migrants in India, have access to HIV and AIDS care, treatment, and support, including free ART. 77 INDIA Bibliography - India ActionAid (2008). A Coalition Report of ActionAid in Partnership with 152 NGOs in India: SHADOW REPORT on Government of India\u2019s II, III, IV & V Combined Report on ICESCR, www.actionaid. org./micrositeAssets/india/assets/shadow_report_final.pdf. Delhi. CATW \u2013 Asia Pacific (2009). Trafficking in Women and Prostitution in the Asia Pacific, www.catwinternational.org/ factbook/India.php. Quezon City, Philippines. Centre for Development Studies (2009). Background Report for National Policy on International Migration Research Unit on International Migration. Trivandrum, Kerala, India. Firoze, F. K. (2003). \u201cTrafficking in Globalised Situation: A South Asian Perspective.\u201d In From Challenges to Opportunities: Responses to Trafficking and HIV/AIDS in South Asia, UNDP. Go