ximately 650 migrant workers leave the country 1 US State Department, The World Factbook, 2009. 2 UNDP, \u201cNepal Human Development Report 2009: State Transformation and Human Development.\u201d 95 Source: Nepal Migration Year Book, 2008, Nepal Institute of Development Studies (NIDS) FIGURE 1: ANNUAL MIGRATION FOR FOREIGN EMPLOYMENT 1993 TO 2008 0 50,000 100,000 150,000 200,000 250,000 300,000 2007-2008 2006-2007 2005-2006 2004-2005 2003-2004 2002-2003 2001-2002 2000-2001 1999-2000 1998-1999 1997-1998 1996-1997 1995-1996 1994-1995 1993-1994 Number of People 3,605 2,161 2,132 3,259 7,745 27,780 35,538 104,738 105,055 91,540 183,929 193,803 229,710 55,018 266,666 for overseas employment every day.3 During the Tenth Five Year Plan period (2002-2007), about 800,000 youths left for foreign employment using formal government channels. It is estimated that the number of youth going abroad without going through non-government procedures is also notable.4 Nepalese migrants working overseas are mainly in the Middle East, East Asia, and South-East Asia. The 2001 Indian Census reported that there were 596,696 Nepali immigrants in India, representing 11.6 percent of the total immigrants received by India. Offi cial statistics on the annual number of registered migrants from 1993 to 2008 confi rm rising trends in migration for foreign employment.5 According to fi gures from the Department of Foreign Employment, 266,666 Nepalis received fi nal approval from the 3 Ministry of Labour and Transport Management, Nepal, 2009; and International Organization for Migration, August 2009; available at www.iom.int/Jahia/activities/asia-and-oceania/sout-and-south-west- asia/nepal. 4 National Planning Commission (NPC), Nepal, Plan Document (three year interim plan), Chapter 17, \u201cLabour Management and Employment Promotion,\u201d 2008. 5 Department of Labour and Employment Promotion, Nepal. government to travel for work abroad through private licensed recruiting agencies and on an individual basis. The number of people seeking permission from the government largely remained strong throughout 2008, with more than 17,500 people leaving every month.6 Over 229,000 people left Nepal as documented migrant workers in 2007, bringing the total estimate of Nepali workers abroad to about 2.6 million, of which 1.6 million had obtained offi cial permission to migrate for employment. An estimated one million were undocumented. Nepal is also a destination country, with an estimated 818,700 migrants working in Nepal, representing 3 percent of the total population.7 Occupational Profi le of Migrants There are no offi cial statistics to show the number 6 NPC, Plan Document. 7 UNDP, Human Development Report 2009, \u201cNepal Country Fact Sheet\u201d; available at hdrstats.undp.org/en/countries/country_fact_ sheets/cty_fs_NPL.html.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "194ba8c8-2a7c-4a3a-9833-dec360193c29": {"__data__": {"id_": "194ba8c8-2a7c-4a3a-9833-dec360193c29", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "HIV and Mobility in South Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-south-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "418982099c6e90534e34330bc77b6a23ca6d61de6f79d0f1c3b8921d92d56401"}, "2": {"node_id": "f4706b8a-10b8-47b3-82e9-39ebc278365a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/hiv-and-mobility-sout