ambodia, sex workers may be referred to Social Affairs Centres under the Ministry of Social Affairs, Veterans, and Youth Rehabilitation.41 In Indonesia, police may refer sex workers to a Social Rehabilitation Centre.42 In Myanmar, sex workers serving prison sentences for prostitution offences may be held at a Vocational Training Centre for Women, where skills training (usually limited to basic literacy, knitting, and basket-making) is provided prior to release.43 Viet Nam has phased out compulsory detention for sex workers. Viet Nam\u2019s National Assembly passed the Law on Administrative Sanctions in 2012, which required authorities to release sex workers detained in rehabilitation centres by July 2013. Sex workers may be fined for administrative violations, but are no longer ordered to undergo detention or compulsory rehabilitation. 38 Fox, J. (2009), Sex laws in Thailand: Laws regulating commercial sex and entertainment places, Thailand Law Forum, at http://www.thailawforum.com/sex-crimes-in-thailand-part2/?print=pdf 39 ESCAP Secretariat (2011), Overview of good practices in promoting multisectoral cooperation and enhancing national capacity in addressing policy and legal barriers to universal access to HIV prevention, treatment, care and support in the Asia-Pacific region, Asia- Pacific High-level Intergovernmental Meeting on the Assessment of Progress against Commitments in the Political Declaration on HIV/AIDS and the Millennium Development Goals, Bangkok: ESCAP (E/ESCAP/HIV/IGM.1/2). 40 The Global Commission on HIV and the Law recommended that governments shut down all compulsory detention or rehabilitation centres for people involved in sex work or for children who have been sexually exploited. Instead, it recommended that governments provide sex workers with evidence-based, voluntary, community empowerment services. Global Commission on HIV and the Law (2012). HIV and the Law: Risks, rights and health, New York: UNDP, p. 43. 41 Keo, C. (2009), Consultancy 