 criminal sanctions for consensual sex between adult men: Brunei Darussalam, Malaysia, Myanmar, and Singapore. These countries have penal codes that are largely based on the nineteenth-century British Penal Code introduced during the colonial era, which includes offences for sodomy or unnatural sex (carnal intercourse \u201cagainst the order of nature\u201d). Sharia law, which applies in Brunei Darussalam, to Muslims in Malaysia, and has been proposed in parts of Indonesia,51 also criminalizes the behaviours of MSM and transgender people.52 Countries that do not criminalize sex between men No laws specifically prohibit male-to-male sex between consenting adults in Cambodia, Indonesia, Lao PDR, the Philippines, Thailand, Timor-Leste, or Viet Nam. These countries were not British colonies and have legal systems significantly influenced by European civil law traditions.53 In Cambodia54, Lao PDR55 and Thailand56 the age of consent is 15 for both homosexual and heterosexual sex. In Viet Nam57 the age of consent is 16 for both homosexual and heterosexual sex. In Timor-Leste58 the age of consent is 17 for both homosexual and heterosexual sex. Although male-to-male sex is not illegal in these countries, some MSM and transgender people may be targeted for harassment or arrest by law enforcement authorities under laws relating to public order or immoral conduct, particularly if they are suspected of involvement in selling sex. In Indonesia, the 50 See Principles on the Application of International Human Rights Law in Relation to Sexual Orientation and Gender Identity (2007), at www. yogyakartaprinciples.org. In relation to state obligations to decriminalize consensual sex between adult males, see Human Rights Committee, Communication No. 488/1992: Australia, U.N. Doc. CCPR/C/50/D/488/1992, Nicholas Toonen v. Australia, 4 April 1994. And in relation to state obligations to transgender people, see judgments of the European Court of Human Rights: B. v. France (25 March 1992), Series A no. 232-C; I. v. the United Kingdom [GC], no. 25680/94 (11 July 2002); Christine Goodwin v. the United Kingdom [GC], no. 28957/95, ECHR 2002-VI. See also UNDP (2013), Discussion paper: Transgender health and human rights, New York: UNDP. 51 E.g., under the draft Sharia criminal regulations (Qanun Jinayat) of Aceh province of Indonesia. 52 A codified form of Sharia law also operates in Mindanao, Philippines, which is understood not to criminalize homosexual conduct. 53 Sodomy offences were removed from the law of France by the codifiers of the French Penal Code in 1806. This affected the laws of French colonies and other nations whose legal systems were influenced by European civil law. 54 Law on Suppression of Human Trafficking and Sexual Exploitation of 2008, article 44; Criminal Code, article 239. See Ministry of Justice (2013), Explanatory Notes for the Law on Suppression of Human Trafficking and Sexual Exploitation, Phnom Penh: Ministry of Justice. 55 Penal Code, article 129. 56 Criminal Code, article 279. 57 Penal Code, article 115. Exceptions apply for sex where the parties are both between 14 and 16. 58 Article 177 provides that it is an offence to practice a sexual act on a minor aged under 14. Article 178 provides that it is an offence for a person who, being an adult, practices a sexual act with a minor aged between 14 and 16 years, taking advantage of the inexperience of the same. Other provisions of the Code refer to minors as being under 17 years (e.g., articles 144, 155, 163), suggesting the phrase between 14 and 16 in article 178 is inclusive of 14 and 16, i.e., 17 is the age of consent to sex (e.g., articles 144, 155, 163, 164). 29 TABLE 3 Legality of sex between men in South-East Asia Country Legality of male-to-male sex Applicable laws Brunei Darussalam Illegal Penal Code, section 377. Carnal intercourse against the order of nature. Penalty: fine or prison sentence up to 10 years.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_templat